### .prettierignore ignores (excludes from formatting) certain files and folders completely.
### .prettierignore file should be created in the root directory of the project.
### Each line in a prettierignore file specifies a pattern.
### .prettierignore uses .gitignore syntax.
# see: https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore#_pattern_format
 
### It’s recommended to have a .prettierignore in your project! 
# This way you can run 'prettier --write .' to make sure that everything is formatted (without        # mangling files you don’t want, or choking on generated files). 
# And, your editor will know which files not to format!

### By default prettier ignores files in version control systems directories and node_modules
## So by default it will be:
# **/.git
# **/.svn
# **/.hg
# **/node_modules

### learn more: https://prettier.io/docs/en/ignore.html



### start IGNORE PATTERN ###
#--------------------------#



# Ignore artifacts:
build
coverage
dist



### end IGNORE PATTERN ###
#------------------------#